title: For Sale:  .303 Australian Lithgow Lee Enfield No.1, Mark III (SMLE) Bolt Action Rifle with Bayonet (never fired, never issued government rifle)
postcontent: For Sale: .303 Bolt Action Rifle - Australian Lithgow - Lee Enfield No. 1 Mark III  Includes: one removable magazine, bayonet, bayonet sheath and canvas covers for both the action and the muzzle.  This is a great collector's piece!  Appraised at Cabelas's as 100% condition rating.  Appraiser considered this rifle to be a never fired, never issued government rifle.  Falls into the very unique collector's item... Includes:  (a)  Bayonet and bayonet sheath:  - 16 5/8" long.  It has a Lithgow 1907 bayonet sheath. The bayonet stamp markings: Line 1:  MKI, Line 2: NWP, Line 3: 42.  There is an oil hole on the pommel which became a feature on the bayonets made after 1922.  This bayonet is stamped on the blade 42, for 1942, therefore the wood handle should be coachwood.  In Nov 1941 production was switched over to the Slazenger Factory and the Queensland Maple that was previously used was then replaced by coachwood.  (Coachwood is a slender tree of the rain forests of Australia and New Guinea, with close-grained timber that has a characteristic caramel scent and is used for cabinetmaking and veneers today.) (b) A Lee-Enfield canvas action cover. It covers the area of the bolt action, the trigger and the removable magazine.  The canvas cover is dated 1951. Appears to be never used. (c) A Lee-Enfield canvas muzzle cover.  It is designed to cover the muzzle.  The cover is dated 1952.  Appears to be never used. RIFLE MARKINGS (a) Serial Number:  The serial number appears in three locations:  (1) Right side of the chamber where the barrel screws in (2) Flatside rear edge of the bolt handle (3) Nosecap for the bayonet.  Each of the serial numbers start with the letter "A" and is followed by 4 digits. (b) Rifle has a brass butt plate. (c) Beneath the bolt handle are the following markings, it is in 5 lines:  (1) MA (2) LITHGOW  (3) SMLE (stands for Small Magazine, Lee-Enfield but called Smelly) (4) III* (5) 1945. (d) The marking "BA" is found in four locations on this rifle:  (1) On the left side of the trigger (2) The bottom of the trigger guard  (3) On the receiver behind the bolt handle.  (4) The front right side of the bolt.  (BA stands for Rifle Factory #2 Bathurst). (e) Marking on the right wing protector of the rear sight is "OA".  (OA stands for Rifle Factory #3 Orange). (f)  Marking on the metal band that surrounds the wood forestock that holds the front sling keeper are the letters "MA".  (MA stands for rifles made after 1926). (g) Stamped into the wood on the bottom side of the front forestock about 2" back from the bayonet mount is "SLAZ 43".  (SLAZ stands for the Slazenger Factory produced in 1943). (h) On the safety, is the Roman Numeral;  III. (i)  The underside of the flip-up rear sights are marked WA 43.  ("WA" stands for the factory at Wellington Annexe and 43 is 1943.) The wood stock is fantastic condition, as well as the metal bluing.  This rifle may have not been fired at all.  It is in unblemished condition. Selling price for the rifle, removable magazine, canvas covers for the action, as well as the muzzle, and the bayonet and sheath - - - all for $650. Location:  Sun Prairie, WI
